          "body": "The Thessalonians' present suffering at the hands of their pagan countrymen is not anomaly but **imitation** — they have become *mimētai* of the Judean churches who suffered at the hands of unbelieving Jews. Paul’s polemic in vv. 15-16 against the Jewish opposition is severe (\"killed the Lord Jesus and the prophets, drove us out, displeasing to God, hostile to all men, hindering the salvation of the Gentiles, filling up the measure of their sins\") — but it is *not* anti-Semitic in the modern sense. Paul is a Jew writing about specific Jewish opponents who had driven him from city to city (Acts 9:23-25; 13:50; 14:5, 19; 17:5-9, 13). The closing line \"wrath has come upon them to the utmost\" (*ephthasen ep' autous hē orgē eis telos*) likely views the eschatological wrath as proleptically inaugurated, with AD 70 still a quarter-century future from this writing (~AD 50)."
